lization sets things up with java, and then there's ClassUtilTest that doesn’t have the necessary property, so I should change it to utilize the missing variant. I want this to be done correctly!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test coverage issues**\\n\\nI'm thinking that the current tests might not be effectively covering the custom loader. I might need to add normal-classloader coverage by adapting existing tests. It could also be helpful to create a new test in NativeLoaderTest without the custom loader that checks the public API `FipsStatus.isReady()` with a property. But if FipsStatus is already ready, it wouldn't matter. However, I’m concerned about the order in which the tests are executed. If NativeLoaderTest runs last, it could be too late to have any effect.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test coverage**\\n\\nI'm figuring out coverage settings and wondering if I should keep each dynamic-access class in its own dedicated Java test file. The rule emphasizes one-to-one coverage. I'm thinking about how to manage tests like ClassUtilTest and FipsStatusTest. There's a concern about the order of execution for NativeLoaderTest. Should I consider renaming it to ensure it runs first? Maybe using `@TestClassOrder` makes sense, but I need to decide carefully on how to handle file naming and configuration.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test initialization**\\n\\nI'm realizing that the one-to-one mapping likely expects a dedicated test for NativeLoader. To address this, I could keep NativeLoaderTest and modify the other tests to avoid initializing FipsStatus first by adjusting properties to be missing. This way, I can still cover active call sites without creating dedicated files for each. However, I need to ensure ClassUtilTest doesn’t block NativeLoader coverage, so isolating it might be necessary, but it feels too broad. JUnit resource locks could be an option too, although class order is not guaranteed.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring test order and coverage**\\n\\nI'm contemplating whether resetting the public settings might be feasible, but it seems unlikely. It looks like the BouncyCastle provider's construction might always trigger FipsStatus. I think setting the property to missing in ClassUtilTest could help cover NativeLoader without issues. If I prioritize FipsStatusTest first, I should use the missing variant rather than relying on java. I wonder what happens if FipsStatus serves as the fallback—will that affect my coverage strategy?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating testing options**\\n\\nI'm thinking about simplifying the testing process by setting missing elements and calling FipsStatus.isReady in the app classloader. But then, what if the app is already ready from previous tests? That might complicate things. Would this test have any effect if it’s the last one? ClassUtil seems to cover everything anyway. Maybe I should consider using `@TestMethodOrder`, but I wonder if there's different JUnit class ordering config in Gradle that I should look into instead.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_mUIuClnYX94waYikxUtRlE0G|fc_0426bda6d0b044020169f9f40eeae4819e9dbea4a60a749666", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bc-fips/2.1.2/src/test/resources -type f -print 2>/dev/null || true && find tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bc-fips/2.1.2/src/test/java/org_bouncycastle/bc_fips -maxdepth 1 -type f -print | sort"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3303, "output": 2457, "cacheRead": 53248, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 59008, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777988582286, "responseId": "resp_0426bda6d0b044020169f9f3e6e368819eba4af555d118edcf"}}
